The [[International Rescue Committee]] (IRC) bestows its '''Freedom Award''' for extraordinary contributions to the cause of [[refugees]] and human [[Freedom (political)|freedom]]. According to the IRC, "The Freedom Award reveals the remarkable ability of an individual to shape history and change for the better a world moving toward freedom for all."<ref name=irc/>

The IRC was founded in 1933 at the request of [[Albert Einstein]],<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.theirc.org/irc-a-glance | title = IRC at a glance | publisher = [[International Rescue Committee]] | accessdate=2010-04-22}}</ref> and made its first Freedom Award in 1957, to German politician [[Willy Brandt]], who went on to win the Nobel Peace Prize.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/peace/laureates/1971/index.html |title=The Nobel Peace Prize 1971 |accessdate=2010-04-22|publisher=Nobel Foundation}}</ref>  The following year, the award was presented to [[Winston Churchill]], British prime minister during the [[Second World War]], for his "dedicated and devoted service to the cause of human liberty".<ref name=churchill/>  The first joint recipients of the award were [[Lane Kirkland]] and his wife Irena who won the prize in 1981.<ref name=first/>  Lane was honored for his "long devotion to the cause of refugees" while Irena was described as "very much a human rights activist".<ref name=first/>  Chinese dissidents [[Li Shuxian]] and [[Fang Lizhi]] were jointly honored in 1991;<ref name=irc/><ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.nytimes.com/1990/06/26/world/statements-by-chinese-dissidents-and-beijing.html?pagewanted=1| work = [[The New York Times]]| accessdate=2010-05-01|date=1990-06-26| title = Statements by Chinese Dissidents and Beijing}}</ref> two American Presidents,  [[George H.W. Bush]] and [[Bill Clinton]] took the prize as a pair in 2005, and film actress [[Angelina Jolie]] and [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees]] High Commissioner [[António Guterres]] received the award together in 2007.<ref name=unhcr/>

Since the first award presentation in 1957, the IRC has made it to 46 recipients, 24 of which were American; the majority of awards have been to politicians.  The 1995 presentation was made ''[[wikt:in absentia|in absentia]]'' to Burmese pro-democracy campaigner and leader of the opposition [[National League for Democracy]] (NLD) party, [[Aung San Suu Kyi]].<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/1950505.stm | title = Profile: Aung San Suu Kyi| publisher = BBC News|accessdate=2010-05-01|date=2009-08-11}}</ref><ref name=un/>  The 2011 award ceremony was held in New York City, at the [[Waldorf-Astoria Hotel]] in November, where the presentation was made to the [[Tom Brokaw|Brokaw family]].<ref name=recent>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rescue.org/blog/2011-freedom-award-honoring-brokaw-family |title=2011 Freedom Award: Honoring the Brokaw Family |publisher=[[International Rescue Committee]] |accessdate=2013-03-27 |date=2011-11-10 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130720162027/http://www.rescue.org/blog/2011-freedom-award-honoring-brokaw-family |archivedate=2013-07-20 |df= }}</ref>  In 2012, [[John C. Whitehead]] received the prize for a second time, the only person to do so.<ref name=irc/>

