{{for|the Icelandic footballer|Ólafur Þórðarson (footballer)}} {{unref|date=August 2015}} {{icelandic name|Óláfr}} '''Óláfr Þórðarson''' was an [[Iceland]]ic [[skald]] and [[scholar]] who was born about 1210 and died in 1259. He is usually called '''Óláfr hvítaskáld''' ("Olaf the white skald") in contrast to a contemporary skald called [[Óláfr Leggsson|Óláfr svartaskáld]] ("Olaf the black skald"). Óláfr was the paternal nephew of [[Snorri Sturluson]] and spent his youth in Snorri's home where he had an important part of his scholarly education. Particular important is his [[Third Grammatical Treatise|Grammatical Treatise]].
After his father's death in 1237, he travelled to [[Norway]], where he stayed with king [[Haakon IV of Norway]] and [[Skule of Norway|Jarl Skule]], before he went to [[Denmark]] and its king [[Valdemar II of Denmark]]. He probably also visited king [[Eric XI of Sweden]]. In 1240, he served as king Haakon's [[housecarl]] in the [[Battle of Oslo (1240)|Battle of Oslo]].
Back in [[Iceland]], he was the island's [[lawspeaker]] from 1252 to 1256. He became a famous skald and composed poems about the three Scandinavian kings, which are partially included in the ''[[Knýtlinga saga]]'', which he probably made from material he collected in Denmark.
